  "prompt": "My iPhone screen broke I have iCloud, would notifications I received transfer over to a replacement or would contacts transfer and notifications gone?",
  "response": "When you set up a replacement iPhone using your iCloud account, several types of data will be transferred, but not all. Here's a breakdown of what you can expect:\n\n### **What Transfers:**\n\n1. **Contacts:** If you have iCloud Contacts enabled, all your saved contacts will automatically sync to the new device.\n2. **Messages:** Text messages, iMessages, and attachments stored in iCloud will be restored.\n3. **Photos and Videos:** If you're using iCloud Photos, your entire photo library will be available on the new iPhone.\n4. **Apps and App Data:** Apps downloaded from the App Store will reinstall, and app data backed up to iCloud will be restored.\n5. **Settings and Preferences:** Wi-Fi passwords, wallpapers, and other settings stored in your iCloud backup will be applied to the new device.\n6. **Emails, Calendars, and Notes:** If these are synced with iCloud, they'll appear on your new iPhone.\n\n### **What Does **Not** Transfer:**\n\n1. **Notifications:** Notifications are transient and are not stored in iCloud backups. This means that the specific notifications you received on your broken iPhone will **not** transfer to the replacement device.\n2. **Live Notifications:** While notifications themselves don't transfer, the apps will continue to send new notifications based on their settings once the device is set up.\n3. **Some App-Specific Data:** Depending on the app, certain data may not be backed up or restored unless it specifically uses iCloud for syncing.\n\n### **Steps to Set Up Your Replacement iPhone:**\n\n1. **Turn on your new iPhone** and follow the on-screen setup instructions.\n2. **Connect to Wi-Fi** to allow the device to access iCloud.\n3. **Sign in with your Apple ID** when prompted.\n4. **Choose to restore from an iCloud backup** and select the most recent backup of your broken iPhone.\n5. **Wait for the restoration process** to complete. This may take some time depending on the size of your backup and your internet speed.\n6. **Finalize settings** as prompted, and your new iPhone should have most of your data, contacts, and settings from the backup.\n\n### **Additional Tips:**\n\n- **Ensure Backups Are Up to Date:** Before switching devices, make sure your broken iPhone had the latest iCloud backup. If your screen is too damaged to navigate, you might need to connect it to a computer and use iTunes/Finder to back it up, if possible.\n  \n- **Check iCloud Sync Settings:** To ensure all your important data (like Contacts, Calendars, Notes, etc.) is synced, go to [iCloud settings](https://support.apple.com/guide/iphone/manage-your-icloud-storage-iph3eb218112/ios) on your new device after setup.\n\nIn summary, while your contacts and other important data will transfer to your replacement iPhone via iCloud, the specific notifications you received on your old device will not. New notifications will resume based on your app settings once the new iPhone is set up.",
